        <p style="font-size:0.95rem;color:var(--muted);line-height:1.75;margin:0;">Anfield is defined by its dense back-to-back Victorian terrace streets, built in the 1870s to 1900s to house the workforce of north Liverpool's industrial docks. Many of these properties have original clay soil stacks and cast iron waste pipes that are now well over 100 years old. Pipe failures, sewer blockages and heating system breakdowns in Anfield properties can spread across adjacent properties quickly given how tightly the terrace rows are built.

The area has a significant private rental sector, with many properties managed by Liverpool City Council through the <a href="https://liverpool.gov.uk/housing/landlords/selective-licensing/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" style="color:var(--orange);font-weight:700;">selective licensing scheme</a>, which requires landlords to maintain properties to a defined standard including working heating and hot water. We issue <a href="/gas-safety-certificate-liverpool" style="color:var(--orange);font-weight:700;">gas safety certificates</a> for Anfield landlords, attend tenant emergency call-outs directly, and provide all documentation required for council compliance. <a href="/boiler-service-liverpool" style="color:var(--orange);font-weight:700;">Annual boiler services</a> from £120 can be booked to cover the full L4 postcode.</p>
